# Build & Deploy — VSIX is built by CI, not locally

This repo's `.vsix` package is built **exclusively** by the
`.github/workflows/build-vsix.yml` GitHub Action, which triggers on every
push to `main` and on `workflow_dispatch`. The maintainer installs the
artifact produced by that workflow into VS Code.

**You MUST NOT** run `npm run build`, `vsce package`, or
`code --install-extension` as part of any task. Local builds are slow
(~3–4 minutes for `npm run build`), produce a 32 MB+ bundle the user has
no use for, and bypass the timezone normalization (`TZ=Europe/London`)
that the CI workflow applies so file mtimes match the maintainer's local
wall clock.

## Deployment flow (the only one you should follow)

1. Make and verify code changes (source edits + corresponding patch in
   `.github/scripts/apply-byok-patches.sh` — see
   [byok-custom-patches](mdc:byok-custom-patches.mdc)).
2. Run the patch script locally to confirm idempotency:
   `bash .github/scripts/apply-byok-patches.sh` — must report every patch
   either as "Patched: …" (fresh apply) or "… already present, skipping"
   (idempotent re-apply). It must NOT exit non-zero.
3. Run any relevant unit tests with `npx vitest run <spec>`.
4. Commit + push to `main` (or open a PR; merging triggers the workflow).
5. The workflow uploads `copilot-custom-build.vsix` as an artifact named
   `copilot-custom-build`. The maintainer downloads and installs it from
   the workflow run page.

## What is OK locally

- `npm run compile` (esbuild dev build) is acceptable when the user
  explicitly asks for it or when you need to verify a tricky bundling
  question that the typecheck can't answer. Most of the time the
  TypeScript compiler (`npm run typecheck`) is enough — esbuild is more
  permissive than `tsc` so passing typecheck is a stronger signal than
  passing esbuild.
- `npx tsc --noEmit -p tsconfig.json` for typecheck on a focused subset.
- Vitest specs.
- Reading the existing `dist/extension.js` to grep for symbols when
  diagnosing bundle-shape problems.

## What is NOT OK locally

- `npm run build` (full production build — slow, no purpose locally).
- `npm run watch:*` (only useful in long-running dev sessions you didn't
  start).
- `vsce package`.
- `code --install-extension <vsix>` — only the maintainer installs.
- Any attempt to "verify the fix works" by rebuilding and reinstalling.
  The way to verify is push → wait for CI → maintainer installs → user
  reports back.

## Version bump

The `.github/scripts/apply-byok-patches.sh` script bumps
`package.json → version` by one patch level on every run (Patch 3). You do
NOT need to manually bump it. Each push to `main` produces a new vsix
whose version is one higher than the previous CI build, which is what
makes VS Code prefer it over the built-in Copilot Chat extension.

## Honest-feedback expectation

If a task requires verifying that a code change actually works at
runtime (e.g. "does the model picker now populate?"), say so honestly.
The right answer is "I've made the change; once you push and install the
new vsix, you'll know." Do NOT pretend a code change has been verified
when the only way to verify it is end-to-end installation.
